pithelium","Transitional epithelium"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cornea is covered by \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-keratinised stratified squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E. This type of epithelium is ideal for the cornea as it provides protection while maintaining transparency essential for vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudostratified columnar epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E is found in respiratory airways but would not provide appropriate protection for the cornea. \u003Cstrong\u003EKeratinised stratified squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E would make the cornea opaque and prevent light transmission. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimple squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate protection for the cornea, while \u003Cstrong\u003Etransitional epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the urinary system and would not be suitable for corneal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe corneal epithelium consists of 5-7 cell layers that are constantly renewed from limbal stem cells. This arrangement allows for both protection and optical clarity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The corneal epithelium is non-keratinised stratified squamous epithelium that is transparent and regularly renewed.","The corneal epithelium consists of 5-7 cell layers that protect the eye while maintaining transparency for light transmission."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Sridhar MS. Anatomy of cornea and ocular surface. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2018 Feb;66(2):190-194. doi: 10.4103/ijo.IJO_646_17. PMID: 29380756; PMCID: PMC5819093.","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-